<subSubSection pageId="26" pageNumber="27" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="26.[151,1437,433,1936]" pageId="26" pageNumber="27">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,274,433,459]" pageId="26" pageNumber="27">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
This species (
<figureCitation box="[433,515,433,459]" captionStart="FIGURES 29–39" captionStartId="27.[151,264,1907,1931]" captionTargetBox="[170,1417,181,1881]" captionTargetId="figure-16@27.[170,1418,181,1883]" captionTargetPageId="27" captionText="FIGURES 29–39. Habitus images of Cyrtocapsus spp. 29, 30, C. grenadensis. 29, male, dorsal aspect. 30, female, dorsal aspect. 31, C. guianus, holotype female, dorsal aspect. 32, 33, C. haitianus. 32, male dorsal aspect. 33, female, dorsal aspect. 34, C. intermedius, female, dorsal aspect. 35, 36, C. lazelli. 35, male, dorsal aspect. 36, female, dorsal aspect. 37, 38, C. marginatus. 37, lectotype male, dorsal aspect. 38, paralectotype female, dorsal aspect. 39, C. mesoamericanus, holotype male, dorsal aspect." pageId="26" pageNumber="27">Fig. 39</figureCitation>
) is recognized by the uniformly black body, the pale yellowish-white antenna and legs, including the coxae, and the parameres (
<figureCitation box="[663,800,469,496]" captionStart="FIGURES 85–98" captionStartId="41.[151,264,1853,1877]" captionTargetBox="[182,1405,489,1830]" captionTargetId="figure-179@41.[182,1405,489,1830]" captionTargetPageId="41" captionText="FIGURES 85–98. Male genitalia of Cyrtocapsus spp. 85, 86, C. mesoamericanus. 85, left paramere. 86, right paramere. 87, 88, C. metafemoratus. 87, left paramere. 88, right paramere. 89, 90, C. pallipes. 89, left paramere. 90, right paramere. 91, 92, C. paraguaiensis. 91 left paramere. 92, right paramere. 93, 94, C. rostratus. 93, left paramere. 94, right paramere. 95, 96, C. schaffneri. 95, left paramere. 96 right paramere. 97, 98, C. spatulatus. 97, left paramere. 98, right paramere." pageId="26" pageNumber="27">Figs. 85, 86</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="26.[151,1437,433,1936]" pageId="26" pageNumber="27">
<taxonomicName box="[199,532,506,532]" class="Insecta" family="Miridae" genus="Cyrtocapsus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="26" pageNumber="27" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="mesoamericanus">
<emphasis box="[199,532,506,532]" italics="true" pageId="26" pageNumber="27">Cyrtocapsus mesoamericanus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is most similar to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bergroth" authorityYear="1910" box="[731,849,505,532]" class="Insecta" family="Miridae" genus="Miccus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="26" pageNumber="27" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="elutipes">
<emphasis box="[731,849,505,532]" italics="true" pageId="26" pageNumber="27">C. elutipes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[862,995,505,531]" captionStart="FIGURES 18–28" captionStartId="14.[151,264,1895,1919]" captionTargetBox="[176,1412,181,1870]" captionTargetId="figure-32@14.[176,1412,181,1871]" captionTargetPageId="14" captionText="FIGURES 18–28. Habitus images of Cyrtocapsus spp. 18, 19, C. discalis, holotype male. 18, dorsal aspect. 19, lateral aspect. 20–22, C. elutipes. 20, male, dorsal aspect. 21, female, dorsal aspect. 22, female, lateral aspect. 23, 24, C. femoralis, lectotype male. 23, dorsal aspect. 24, lateral aspect. 25, 26, C. fiuzai. 25, male, dorsal aspect. 26, female, dorsal aspect. 27, 28, C. glabratus, holotype male. 27, dorsal aspect. 28, lateral aspect." pageId="26" pageNumber="27">Figs. 20–22</figureCitation>
) in having a black body, pale yellowishwhite antenna and legs (including the coxae), but 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bergroth" authorityYear="1910" box="[730,852,541,568]" class="Insecta" family="Miridae" genus="Miccus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="26" pageNumber="27" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="elutipes">
<emphasis box="[730,852,541,568]" italics="true" pageId="26" pageNumber="27">C. elutipes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is distinctly smaller, the left paramere (
<figureCitation box="[1315,1400,541,568]" captionStart="FIGURES 58–70" captionStartId="39.[151,264,1774,1798]" captionTargetBox="[170,1418,181,1750]" captionTargetId="figure-16@39.[170,1418,181,1750]" captionTargetPageId="39" captionText="FIGURES 58–70. Male genitalia of Cyrtocapsus spp. 58–60, C. apicalis. 58, left paramere. 59, endosoma. 60, right paramere. 61, 62, C. atrametatibialis. 61, left paramere. 62, right paramere. 63, 64, C. caligineus. 63, left paramere. 64, right paramere. 65, 66, C. columbiensis. 65, left paramere. 66, right paramere. 67, 68, C. elutipes. 67, left paramere. 68, right paramere. 69, 70, C. femoralis. 69, left paramere. 70, right paramere." pageId="26" pageNumber="27">Fig. 67</figureCitation>
) is elongate and apically hooked, and the right paramere (
<figureCitation box="[762,843,577,604]" captionStart="FIGURES 58–70" captionStartId="39.[151,264,1774,1798]" captionTargetBox="[170,1418,181,1750]" captionTargetId="figure-16@39.[170,1418,181,1750]" captionTargetPageId="39" captionText="FIGURES 58–70. Male genitalia of Cyrtocapsus spp. 58–60, C. apicalis. 58, left paramere. 59, endosoma. 60, right paramere. 61, 62, C. atrametatibialis. 61, left paramere. 62, right paramere. 63, 64, C. caligineus. 63, left paramere. 64, right paramere. 65, 66, C. columbiensis. 65, left paramere. 66, right paramere. 67, 68, C. elutipes. 67, left paramere. 68, right paramere. 69, 70, C. femoralis. 69, left paramere. 70, right paramere." pageId="26" pageNumber="27">Fig. 68</figureCitation>
) is somewhat L-shaped with the main body elongate oval and apically rounded, whereas 
<taxonomicName box="[563,785,614,640]" class="Insecta" family="Miridae" genus="Cyrtocapsus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="26" pageNumber="27" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="mesoamericanus">
<emphasis box="[563,785,614,640]" italics="true" pageId="26" pageNumber="27">C. mesoamericanus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is larger, the left paramere (
<figureCitation box="[1111,1194,613,640]" captionStart="FIGURES 85–98" captionStartId="41.[151,264,1853,1877]" captionTargetBox="[182,1405,489,1830]" captionTargetId="figure-179@41.[182,1405,489,1830]" captionTargetPageId="41" captionText="FIGURES 85–98. Male genitalia of Cyrtocapsus spp. 85, 86, C. mesoamericanus. 85, left paramere. 86, right paramere. 87, 88, C. metafemoratus. 87, left paramere. 88, right paramere. 89, 90, C. pallipes. 89, left paramere. 90, right paramere. 91, 92, C. paraguaiensis. 91 left paramere. 92, right paramere. 93, 94, C. rostratus. 93, left paramere. 94, right paramere. 95, 96, C. schaffneri. 95, left paramere. 96 right paramere. 97, 98, C. spatulatus. 97, left paramere. 98, right paramere." pageId="26" pageNumber="27">Fig. 85</figureCitation>
) is stoutly C-shaped, and the right paramere (
<figureCitation box="[420,502,649,676]" captionStart="FIGURES 85–98" captionStartId="41.[151,264,1853,1877]" captionTargetBox="[182,1405,489,1830]" captionTargetId="figure-179@41.[182,1405,489,1830]" captionTargetPageId="41" captionText="FIGURES 85–98. Male genitalia of Cyrtocapsus spp. 85, 86, C. mesoamericanus. 85, left paramere. 86, right paramere. 87, 88, C. metafemoratus. 87, left paramere. 88, right paramere. 89, 90, C. pallipes. 89, left paramere. 90, right paramere. 91, 92, C. paraguaiensis. 91 left paramere. 92, right paramere. 93, 94, C. rostratus. 93, left paramere. 94, right paramere. 95, 96, C. schaffneri. 95, left paramere. 96 right paramere. 97, 98, C. spatulatus. 97, left paramere. 98, right paramere." pageId="26" pageNumber="27">Fig. 86</figureCitation>
) is elongate, weakly curved, and narrowed apically. I can distinguish females of 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Miridae" genus="Cyrtocapsus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="26" pageNumber="27" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="mesoamericanus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="26" pageNumber="27">C. mesoamericanus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from those of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bergroth" authorityYear="1910" box="[504,624,685,712]" class="Insecta" family="Miridae" genus="Miccus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="26" pageNumber="27" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="elutipes">
<emphasis box="[504,624,685,712]" italics="true" pageId="26" pageNumber="27">C. elutipes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
only by the clearly larger size.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="26" pageNumber="27" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="26.[151,1437,433,1936]" pageId="26" pageNumber="27">
